## Public Health and Safety Considerations

### Preventing Unsafe Abortions and Maternal Mortality

One of the strongest arguments for legal abortion is the protection of women's health and lives. Before legalization, many women resorted to unsafe, clandestine abortions, leading to high rates of mortality and morbidity. The World Health Organization estimated that in 2008 alone, approximately 47,000 women died worldwide due to unsafe abortions ([Essays.io, n.d.](https://essays.io/arguments-for-and-against-abortion-essay-example/)).

Legal abortion ensures access to medically supervised procedures, significantly reducing health risks. For example, during the first trimester, abortion's mortality rate is more than five times lower than that of childbirth ([UMKC Law, n.d.](http://law2.umkc.edu/faculty/projects/ftrials/conlaw/roeargs.htm)).

### Equality and Access

Legal abortion also addresses socioeconomic disparities. When abortion is illegal or heavily restricted, low-income women disproportionately suffer, as they cannot afford to travel to obtain safe procedures or resort to dangerous self-induced abortions. This creates a discriminatory effect where only wealthier women can access safe abortions ([KnowsWhy.com, 2010](https://www.knowswhy.com/why-should-abortion-be-legal/)).

