## Social and Historical Context

### Historical Legal Landscape

Abortion was widely illegal in the United States by the late 19th century, with laws primarily targeting providers rather than women. These laws aimed to protect women and fetuses from harm but did not recognize women's reproductive autonomy ([Pew Research Center, 2013](https://www.pewforum.org/2013/01/16/a-history-of-key-abortion-rulings-of-the-us-supreme-court/)).

The women's rights movement of the 1960s, alongside court decisions expanding privacy rights (e.g., *Griswold v. Connecticut* in 1965), set the stage for *Roe v. Wade*. States began repealing abortion bans, recognizing the need for safe, legal access ([History.com Editors, 2019](https://www.history.com/topics/womens-rights/roe-v-wade)).

### Impact of Legalization

Since *Roe*, abortion has remained legal nationwide, though states have imposed various restrictions. Legal abortion has contributed to significant public health benefits, including reduced maternal mortality and morbidity. It also supports women's participation in society and the workforce by allowing reproductive choices ([Wikipedia, 2024](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Philosophical_aspects_of_the_abortion_debate)).

